docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump appeared to take a step back from his administration’s “maximum pressure” campaign against Iran on Wednesday, leaving open the possibility of easing economic sanctions before starting new nuclear negotiations with Tehran.

headline.main: Trump Leaves Open Possibility of Easing Iranian Sanctions to Spur Nuclear Talks
headline.print_headline: U.S. Leaves Open Plan of Easing Sanctions on Iran to Spur Nuclear Talks

docs.abstract: The former intelligence contractor, who disclosed surveillance secrets in 2013, failed to submit his book for prepublication review.
docs.snippet: The former intelligence contractor, who disclosed surveillance secrets in 2013, failed to submit his book for prepublication review.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Justice Department sued the former intelligence contractor Edward Snowden on Tuesday, seeking to seize his proceeds from his new memoir because he did not submit the manuscript for review before it was published so officials could make sure it contained no classified information.

headline.main: U.S. Tries to Seize Edward Snowden’s Proceeds From New Memoir
headline.print_headline: U.S. Sues for Royalties From Snowden’s Memoir

docs.abstract: Congressional Democrats insisted that a new bill to make it easier for the police to take guns away from people deemed dangerous must be paired with an expansion of background checks.
docs.snippet: Congressional Democrats insisted that a new bill to make it easier for the police to take guns away from people deemed dangerous must be paired with an expansion of background checks.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Chuck Schumer, the Democratic leader, put the brakes on Republicans’ quick embrace of “red flag” laws as a response to last weekend’s gun violence, saying on Wednesday that any gun-related legislation moving through the Senate must be accompanied by a House bill requiring background checks on all gun purchasers.

headline.main: Democrats Warn That Federal ‘Red Flag’ Law Would Not Be Enough
headline.print_headline: Democrats to Republicans: ‘Red Flag’ Bill Isn’t Enough

docs.abstract: Federal authorities say they want to employ the same approach used in battling global extremism. But there are political and civil rights concerns.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Law enforcement officials have sounded the alarm for months: Homegrown terrorism, including by white supremacists, is now as big a threat as terrorism from abroad. But the mass shooting in El Paso last weekend, the largest domestic terrorist attack against Hispanics in modern history, has made it glaringly clear how poorly prepared the country is to fight it.

headline.main: Shootings Renew Debate Over How to Combat Domestic Terrorism
headline.print_headline: Fight Turns to Domestic Terror Without a Clear Path to Follow

docs.abstract: President Trump’s comment this week that Jews who vote for Democrats are disloyal echoes an anti-Semitic trope that has persisted for centuries.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s comment this week that Jews who vote for Democrats are disloyal echoes an anti-Semitic trope that has persisted for centuries.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump said this week that American Jews who chose to vote for Democrats were being disloyal, he was flirting with a notion that has fueled anti-Semitism for generations and has been at the root of some of the most brutal violence inflicted upon Jews in their history.

headline.main: The Toxic Back Story to the Charge That Jews Have a Dual Loyalty
headline.print_headline: The Toxic Back Story to the Charge That Jews Have a Dual Loyalty
